defaultWe welcome the chance to submit evidence to the Committee’s inquiry
default. 
defaultIn general, it is
default road users
default who are most likely to be injured or killed by accidents at level crossings.  However
default,
default there are cases where a collision between a train
default and a road vehicle has resulted in a derailment and subsequent multiple fatalities and serious injuries to a train’s passengers and crew, Ufton Nervet in 2004 being the most recent UK example. In addition, a number of train drivers have been killed in col
defaultlisions where there were no passenger fatalities due to their location at the very front of the train. Train drivers and others can also suffer serious psychological or psychiatric injury after witnessing an accident at a level crossing
default.
default3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAccording to the 
defaultOffice of Rail Regulation
default (ORR)
default, the independent safety and economic regulator for Britain's railways, there are approximately 9
default,
default000 level crossings in Great Britain.
default Network Rail manages just over 6
default,
default500 active, open crossings.
default The rest are located on he
defaultritage railways, metro systems and industrial railways.
defaultAre current safety measures at level crossings adequate? How should they be improved? default4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe
default evidence suggests that 
defaultBritain’s mainline railway is the best in the EU at managing risks at level crossings.
default 
defaultT
defaulthis is a conclusion reached by the ORR and their 
defaultHealth and Safety Report 2013
default 
defaultrecords that there has been a long-term trend of decreasing risk at level crossings and that Network Rail is on-target to meet its 25% reduction in level crossing risk over Co
defaultntrol Period 4 (CP4) 2009-14, as measured by its own model.
default 
defaultThis view
default is echoed by the Rail Accident Investigation Branch who 
defaultfind 
defaultthat the UK’s mainline railway has a good overall level crossing safety record relative to the other European Union Member 
defaultStates.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultT
defaulthere should be no complacency
default.
default 
defaultBritain’s level crossings still account for nearly half of the catastrophic train accident risk on the railway
default and 
default there were nine level cros
defaultsing user fatalities in 2012/13 
default- four pedestrians users and five road 
defaultvehicle users.
default 
default There were also seven major 
defaultinjuries, 53 reported minor injuries and 17 reports of shock or trauma. There were ten collisions between trains and road vehicles. The total amount of harm at level crossings in 2012/13 showed an increase compa
defaultred with the last two years, but was below the ten-year average. There were no passenger or workforce fatalities and the last level crossing accident resulting in train occupant fatalities occurred in 2004.
default&#xa0;
default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFurther improvements
default 
defaultcould be made by
default new equip
defaultment, better management,
default closer working and a clearer division of responsibilities between Network Rail and those responsible for roads
default,
default and a general simplification of legal processes governing the closure of level crossings. 
defaultThe challenge is to deliver i
defaultmprovement at an affordable cost.
default 
defaultNetwork Rail is spending £130m to improve level crossing safety during Control Period 4 (1 April 2009 - 31 March 2014).
defaultIn addition to bridges and underpasses what other cost-effective measures can be introduced to replacedefault or improve safety at level crossings?default7.
